            <div n="1">
                <head>
                    <hi rendition="#k">A Letter from Baron Humboldt.</hi>
                </head>
                <p>&#x2014;This distinguished<lb break="yes"/>individual has written a letter to Mr. Aqassiez. the author<lb break="yes"/>of an important work, called &#x201C;Contributions to the National<lb break="yes"/>History of the United States.&#x201D; The Baron says:&#x2014;The generous<lb break="yes"/>interest displayed in the U. S., when your vast enterprise was<lb break="yes"/>announced, my excellent friend, has given a very flattering<lb break="yes"/>proof of the ever-increasing intellectual interest, and of the<lb break="yes"/>honourable confidence manifested for talent and a noble<lb break="yes"/>character. I am charged by the king, who feels the import-<lb break="no"/>ance of your former labours, and retains for you the affec-<lb break="no"/>tionate esteem which he showed personally, when he saw you<lb break="yes"/>among your collections, to place his name at the head of<lb break="yes"/>your numerous subscribers. He hopes that an excursion<lb break="yes"/>across the &#x201C;Atlantic Valley&#x201D; may some day conduct you,<lb break="yes"/>who have boldly scaled the lofty summits of the Alps, to the<lb break="yes"/>&#x201C;historic hill&#x201D; of Sans Sonci. I have it much at heart that<lb break="yes"/>you should allow an extract of this not very legible letter to<lb break="yes"/>be published, since it contains the sincere proof of the lively<lb break="yes" />satisfaction with which I have welcomed your great and<lb break="yes"/>useful enterprise.</p>
            </div>
            <lb break="yes"/>
        </body>
